The Response to CO2 Change\
\
We learned in Chapter 1 that Svante Arrhenius was the first person to attempt a calculation of the effect of doubling \\(\\text\{CO\}_2\\) in the atmosphere. But his data and methods were not really up to the challenge. It was therefore something of an accident that he got a climate sensitivity roughly consistent with current estimates. In order to calculate it properly one really needs good radiative absorption and emission data on atmospheric gases, a good mathematical model of the atmosphere, and a computer to run the calculations. Arrhenius didn\'92t have any of these. But Manabe and colleagues did, and they were the first to make a realistic calculation of what has come to be called Earth\'92s climate sensitivity.\
\
Manabe used the same model as in his previous paper discussed above, to estimate the atmosphere\'92s response to doubling and halving \\(\\text\{CO\}_2\\). The reference or control simulation used 300 ppm of \\(\\text\{CO\}_2\\) (approximately the atmosphere\'92s value in the 1960s), and doubling and halving amounts of 600 ppm and 150 ppm. Just like the previous simulations they ran each of these until they reached an equilibrium state. The figure below shows the vertical profiles of temperature in radiative-convective equilibrium from these three experiments.\
\
FIG: manabe-2xco2.png\
\
For the control simulation with a \\(\\text\{CO\}_2\\) concentration of 300 ppm, surface temperature is 288 K (~15\'b0C), which is similar to the observed global mean surface temperature. In response to doubling  \\(\\text\{CO\}_2\\) to 600 ppm, the surface temperature increased by 2.4\'b0C.  In response to halving \\(\\text\{CO\}_2\\), surface temperature decreased by 2.3\'b0C. Note that unlike more recent calculations with more accurate models, the lapse rate in this model stays the same, at 6.5\'b0C/km, instead of decreasing, on a global average, like we learned about in the last chapter. This is because of how the \'91convective adjustment\'92 was calculated in the model.\
\
So Manabe calculated a climate sensitivity of about 2.4\'b0C. This is fairly close to the current best estimate of 3\'b0C using far more sophisticated models.\
\
You may have noticed from the figure above that as you increase \\(\\text\{CO\}_2\\) the stratosphere actually cools, which is the opposite of the troposphere. We can explain this result by consulting the figure we saw before which shows the radiative heating and cooling effects of different gases:\
\
